    <title>Combined summary - MuSig2 BIP</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T18:51:32.938872+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-April/020198.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>A team of researchers including Yannick Seurin, Tim Ruffing, Elliott Jin, and Jonas Nick discovered an attack against the latest version of BIP MuSig2. The vulnerability allows an attacker to forge a signature for any message and any aggregate public key that contains the signer's individual public key under certain conditions. However, this discovery does not invalidate the security proof of the scheme in the MuSig2 paper.The MuSig2 BIP draft proposes a solution to handle identical public keys in a multi-signature scheme. Simply aborting in the presence of identical public keys would allow for a disruptive signer to permanently DoS-attack a session by copying the public key of another signer. However, implementing this solution requires added complexity due to the MuSig2* optimization, which ultimately allows for the identification and removal of disruptive signers, reducing complexity for MuSig2 users. Implementing the Taproot tweak with the key aggregation algorithm requires making the pre-tweaked combined key available to the caller, but the specified algorithms in the BIP unnecessarily recompute certain values. A precise specification has been made to replace the description of this signing mode in a PR that was opened. Additionally, Jonas Nick and Brandon discussed a fragment of the BIP that describes a shortcut for a specific signer to send their nonces last, simplifying the implementation of certain protocols.A developer has praised Jonas Nick and co-authors for publishing an excellent technical specification on the much-anticipated musig2 BIP. The BIP draft has undergone significant improvements since its initial publication, thanks to feedback from the mailing list and development git repository. There are now multiple implementations in place, and no major changes or features have been requested in recent weeks. The authors of the BIP would like to express their gratitude to numerous individuals who provided valuable feedback during the drafting process.In an email exchange between Jonas Nick and waxwing/AdamISZ, they discussed the idea of key aggregation failing if duplicate keys are found. In simpler terms, the taproot interaction is defined as a function of the internal key itself. This is known as the taproot tweak and is denoted as h_tapTeak(internalKey || rootHash). A user named Waxwing/AdamISZ contacted Jonas Nick via email thanking him for the BIP draft and requesting some clarification about identical pubkeys and its relation to MuSig2* optimization.The MuSig2 BIP draft has been updated to fix the vulnerability and ensure that users cannot accidentally violate the requirement of determining the (potentially tweaked) secret key before calling NonceGen. Waxwing/AdamISZ also contacted Jonas Nick via email to discuss identical pubkeys and its relation to MuSig2* optimization. A merged PR was acknowledged in an email sent by AdamISZ to Jonas and bitcoin-dev on May 26th, 2022 at 12:34.</summary>
